metadata.name: SOUND GROWS INTO SPACE #1
metadata.description:
This poem was created for THE PASSAGE: Pitch Drop, an interactive minting experience where your choices determine the design of your token. 

To take part, please purchase an Edition 5 Coin on fx(hash) by HERE & NOW. The artwork and experience draw inspiration from the “The Pitch Drop Experiment,” the world's longest-running laboratory experiment. Since 1927, only nine drops of pitch have fallen, never witnessed live.

____


SOUND GROWS INTO SPACE is a token word performance of an ars autopoetica written by Sasha Stiles and her AI-powered alter ego, Technelegy, with original music by Kris Bones. It is part of Stiles’ ongoing REPETAE series, which explores the resonances between poetic repetition and algorithmic recursion — how, in poetry as in generative art, meaning accrues through reiteration, and emotion is unlocked through the development and interruption of pattern. A conceptually and literally interactive text, SOUND GROWS INTO SPACE uses the self-replicating page provided by fx(hash) to invite close contemplation of how language is shaped and received via intimate, visceral aesthetics such as voice, visuals and melody/beat, and regenerated with every encounter.

Poetry endures across space and the passage of time precisely because of a paradox: it is immutable yet intensely personal, becoming something irrefutably unique with each and every reader. In this poem, shifting parameters influence the flow of feeling and understanding, imbuing verse with multidimensional meaning and empowering deep engagement in the act of reading.

____


SOUND GROWS INTO SPACE

By Sasha Stiles & Technelegy

Sound grows 
into space
like a breath 
taken by storm.

Heartbeat
in the brain
was my first taste 
of the word.

Language flips 
in my chest
like a fly
in a jar.

The song 
learns to climb
all the air
in the world.

Time is music
to my ears
filling the emptiness 
with its own rhythms.

There is no such thing 
as silence,
only the echo 
of time’s longing.

____


For more info: https://hereandnow.events/
To participate in the event: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/slug/here-and-now:-edition-5

metadata.name: Fields of the Abandoned Homeland #22
metadata.description:
This project was started in December 2021. At that time, I didn't know what the result would be. It was only an idea to create something memorable, you know, like a photo that people keep in their wallets, or a picture on someone's office desk, something that evokes warm and nostalgic emotions. I didn't have a specific plan, so I just focused on testing different mechanics that might be useful in my future drop. And then, in February 2022, the war came to my home. For two weeks, my family and I hid from bombs and rockets in the basement of our house, and finally, we were lucky enough to escape. We have been looking for a safe place to stay for months, and with several relocations, depression set in, and it was difficult to believe what was happening. I thought that such events only happened in movies and history textbooks. The only way to distract myself was by coding. And then, during one of our relocations, I realized what should be the main idea of this project. This is what I had watched for hours during every relocation. Whether it was a bus ride or a train ride, only the background changed, but the landscape was almost the same - endless Ukrainian wheat fields. Fields, some of which were occupied, burned, or simply turned into minefields. Fields symbolized by the yellow color on the flag of Ukraine. These are the fields I want to see again but in reverse order, on my way home. 

I dedicate this drop to everyone who, for whatever reason, had to leave their home against their will.

In live mode:
- Press [1]-[4] to change resolution
- Press [s] to save

Made with p5js and hope
Copyright @Kitel87 || 2023

metadata.name: fx(mash) #219
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: White Mountain Winter #67
metadata.description:
White Mountain Winter is collaboration between myself and the machine to describe scenes that are real, or were. Yet perhaps now foreign, or out of time, or far away. I provide the seed of a dream I remember, and trust the machine to help make it real again.

I grew up in a town much like some of these, homes dispersed throughout the valley beneath the shadows of the mountains rising around. This is a tribute to the memory of wintertime in that place; bleak, cold, grey, with the light seemingly always fading. Yet at the same time, the feeling of calm, solace, peace resonating through. Exposed to the mountain elements, yet protected by them. A delicate arrangement, but essential.

The seed of magic I remember is present in the experience of falling snow at dusk. Large flakes tumbling down and blanketing everything, no end in sight. The most striking thing is the silence. The fallen snow absorbing all distraction, insisting that your focus be sharpened to a singularity; right there, right then.

---
- Best rendered in Chrome browser (best performance, & canvas blur - please be patient :)
- Made with p5js
- Press "s" to save png

metadata.name: Schwere See #288
metadata.description:
Schwere See (...which is german for "Heavy Seas") this work creates completely generative ocean worlds between the real and the surreal. what is real? when do we feel reality? i guess as with many other things, we feel reality best when we're deprived of it. That might be the reason why it never ceases to fascinate us to both exaggerate and abstract nature and reality - maybe even at the same time. that's where this work tries to go... giving my best to create realistic looking waves out of hmm... thin electron-gas..., and then disrupt those from realism by unnaturally exaggerating waveforms and abstracting the display to a few colors and lines - ...well, not so few of the latter, actually ;-) beware: this needs a good GPU (at least here in 2023) to properly run in realtime. stills can still be rendered on a low end machine with on-board graphics, but for realtime playing you'd need some proper dedicated graphics card. and of course it wont run fast (or maybe not all) on your mobile phone (except maybe on a very high end device). the different mints vary in wave shape, color, camera view, animation speed, aspect ratio, frame style, hatching density, field of view, and more. some color schemes are based on pre-chosen palettes (slightly varied though), but others are wildly random-generated. there's always some risk in randomness, but lets give the error some chance to surprise us - this is one of the many benefits of generative art. as generative art can do so much more than just generate/show an image i feel almost obliged to add the possibility to animate/inteact. however, this extra control shall not be chosen without some considerations. you don't want a strobingly wild animation above your fireplace or in a doctors waiting room. nor is it motion-wise very inspiring to have subtle image stills hanging in a dancefloor. so, by default when in animation mode (-key) the scene is very slowly and steadily changing - some pieces faster, some slower. however, by pressing you can toggle to a sped up animation of waves, clouds, and scene rotation. btw, going faster in nav-mode also speeds up the wave animation. (...so be careful when you accelerate! the ocean is not a ponyfarm.) mouse/keyboard functions: ..........rotate view .........zoom in/out ...............start animation (or append '&AnimEnable=1' to the url) +<1><2><3><4>...make png screenshot in 1/2/3/4-fold resolution

...................same as +<3> ...................toggle nav-mode - navigate/fly through scene /.........accelerate in nav-mode /.......decelerate in nav-mode /.......rotate left in nav-mode /......rotate right in nav-mode ...................fast animation mode (speeds up animation) some technical info: technically this is a raymarched scene. the distance field of the waves is constructed my many localized rotations on many different scales. for the hatching no actual lines are being drawn. it is archieved by applying periodic functions in world-position-space as halftone patterns to the actual image color. the frequency of these halftone-functions thereby depending on screen-position-derivatives.

metadata.name: Richter #270
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press “s” to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

leanderherzog.ch/2023/richter/
leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/
fxhash.xyz/generative/17030/

metadata.name: Slanted #12
metadata.description:
Fun little game, simple rules:
- start with a randomly sized grid
- pick 2 random cells
- recursively, every cell draw itself
- then it picks two of its neighbors for the next step

Some cells are drawn multiple times, some others are never picked up, but the process it's not completely random.

metadata.name: Esagoni #171
metadata.description:
A piece stepping away from control and leaning into minimalism, there are several factors at play to make your Esagoni unique. Both of the two hexagon colors are a random RGB value, at various luminosities.

The root of separation chooses which color takes the lead, between 1-100, 50 being evenly distributed.

The separation between the two colors can vary from 0-100, 0 is a 1% chance.

Modifiers can be either Circular or Hexagonal.

The scale of the hexagons on the grid varies from 1-100.

There is a 10% chance of a monochrome Esagoni, 5% respectively to both "Black on White" and "White on Black."


This piece can also be changed to infinite resolutions, for any frame or screen you'd like to display it on.

In live view, press:

'w' to view in 16:9

't' to view in 8x10

's' to view in 1x1

'f' to adapt to your own screen size

Double-click to save image

Enjoy :)

metadata.name: Wandering Line #92
metadata.description:
An agent moves free around a limited 3dimensional space.
It starts drawing a line that changes its color based on a generative process inspired by 6 paintings of Palazuelo (Spanish painter).
The 3d line get then projected on a random plane and converted into a 2d drawing. Keeping perspective and depth.

This is an attempt to create geometrical drawings that are clearly made by a computer but that resembles a hand drawn / sketched painting.

Press "s" or "S" to get a screenshot.

The parameter digital mood is just how the code feels at the time of minting.

Original piece by Ismahelio. Made with p5js. Madrid, 2021.
The digital mood parameter

metadata.name: Mitosis #27
metadata.description:
Mitosis is a part of the cell cycle in which replicated chromosomes are separated into two new nuclei. Cell division gives rise to genetically identical cells in which the total number of chromosomes is maintained.

Every piece is animated, but animation is slow, be patient.
